{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"463d4409-a019-402a-b806-fd2440edb9c1","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, use the **OS-native crash reporting** instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** – run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash logs** – macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n3. **Locate the core file** – if `ulimit` was set, look for `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **Ensure sufficient disk space** – core files can be large; `/cores` must be writable.\n\n6. **SIP note** – System Integrity Protection may block core dumps for some processes. You can check with `csrutil status`.\n\nThis gives you a native stack trace. For managed-frame symbolication, you'll also want the `.dsym` / debug symbols from your NativeAOT publish.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f31d92a-ef6e-4f5f-8db7-a25a4972b6c4","outputTokens":313,"requestId":"204B:2A854:7555FE:8850C7:69F0128C"},"id":"6576c7db-91d5-4b01-8b70-543e67cb921d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:51:17.319Z","parentId":"cec7ded1-4399-4e79-ba4b-3a42b62f53b1"}
